    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with **Corbin Carroll** serving as our undisputed anchor. With a score of 80.85, **Corbin Carroll** possesses the ideal profile for our aggressive stealing strategy, bolstered by a plus-matchup against Pop and a favorable 1.88s catcher pop time, which offsets the minor efficiency penalty to highlight his elite offensive ceiling. Similarly, **Josh Naylor** (69.07) and **Brice Turang** (66.23) are locked in as core starters. **Brice Turang**\u2019s leadoff placement (+10% order bonus) and the exploitable 4.40 xERA of Littell provide a high-floor base for our counting stats. We are also monitoring the platoon edge for **Mickey Moniak** (61.90), whose 14% platoon bonus against the right-handed Pivetta makes him a high-leverage start, despite the middling park factors.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s card was the exclusion of **Seiya Suzuki** (45.23) from the starting nine. While **Seiya Suzuki** posted a respectable baseline, his utility was suppressed by a difficult matchup against Chandler and the relative efficiency of our current outfield mix; he remains our primary pivot should any last-minute lineup shifts occur. We are proceeding with caution regarding **Dalton Rushing** (40.61) and **James Wood** (51.65), as both face elite arms in deGrom and Woodruff, respectively. While **James Wood**\u2019s 100% stolen base opportunity rating (due to the pitcher's slow delivery) keeps him in the lineup, we are watching the weather and potential bullpen usage closely to ensure we preserve our game caps. Conversely, **Vinnie Pasquantino** (55.60) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (55.91) are on the lower end of our starting threshold; while they provide solid volume, their reliance on favorable platoon splits against Taylor and Peralta makes them secondary priority plays compared to the explosive upside offered by **Corbin Carroll** and **Brice Turang**.",
